# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: detlev-bronk
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Previously at the University of California, Berkeley, he served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] His academic research focuses on nanomaterials, particularly nanocrystal fabrication for biomedical and renewable energy applications.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Paul Alivisatos was born in Chicago, Illinois, where he lived until the age of 10, when his family moved to Athens, Greece.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He returned to the United States to attend the University of Chicago in the late 1970s.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos received a Bachelor of Arts degree (with honors) with a major in chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1981 and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry from the University of California, Berkeley, in 1986.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral advisor at Berkeley was Charles B.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] His doctoral thesis was titled *The photophysical properties of molecules near metal and semiconductor surfaces*.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] After receiving his doctorate, Alivisatos joined AT&T Bell Labs working with Louis E.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Brus, and began research in the field of nanotechnology.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos returned to the University of California, Berkeley in 1988 as an assistant professor of chemistry.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He was promoted to associate professor in 1993 and to full professor in 1995.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] In administrative roles, Alivisatos served as the 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory from 2009 to 2016, as the university's interim vice chancellor for research from 2016 to 2017, and as executive vice chancellor and provost from 2017 to 2021.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] In August 2013, he was appointed as Samsung Distinguished Professor in Nanoscience and Nanotechnology Research.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He was also the founding director of the Kavli Energy Nanosciences Institute (ENSI).
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos joined the Materials Sciences Division at Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in 1991.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He served as associate laboratory director for physical sciences from 2005 to 2007.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] In 2008, he became deputy director, and he stepped in as interim director after Steven Chu left to become United States Secretary of Energy under the first Obama administration.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] On November 19, 2009, Alivisatos was appointed 7th director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He refocused the lab on renewable energy and climate research, oversaw new facilities, deepened ties to the national innovation ecosystem, and advanced collaborations that sped technology transfer across industries from autos to medicine.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] On March 23, 2015, he announced that he would step down from the directorship once a successor was named.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] On February 26, 2021, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago named Alivisatos as the incoming 14th president of the University of Chicago, with his term beginning on September 1, 2021.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He succeeded Robert Zimmer, who served as the university president from July 2006 to August 2021.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to the office of the president, he was named the John D.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] MacArthur Distinguished Service Professor, chair of the Board of Governors of Argonne National Laboratory, and chair of the Board of Directors of Fermi Forward Discovery Group LLC, which operates the Fermi National Accelerator Laboratory.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] On September 24, 2025, the Board of Trustees of the University of Chicago extended Alivisatos's presidency through June 2030.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is an internationally recognized authority on nano chemistry in the synthesis of semiconductor quantum dots and multi-shaped artificial nanostructures.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Further, he is a world expert on the chemistry of nanoscale crystals; one of his papers (Science, 271: 933–937, 1996) has been cited over 13,800 times.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He is also an expert on how these can be applied, for example as biological markers (e.g., Science, 281: 2013–16, 1998; a paper cited over 10,900 times).
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition, his use of DNA in this area (DNA nanotechnology) has shown the surprising versatility of this molecule.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He has used it to direct crystal growth and create new materials, as in Nature, 382: 609–11, 1996, and even to measure nanoscale distances (see Nature Nanotechnology, 1: 47–52, 2006).
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] In February 2011, Alivisatos was ranked fifth among the world's top 100 chemists for the period 2000–2010 in the list released by Thomson Reuters.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He is widely recognized as being the first to demonstrate that semiconductor nanocrystals can be grown into complex two-dimensional shapes, as opposed to simple one-dimensional spheres.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos proved that controlling the growth of nanocrystals is the key to controlling both their size and shape.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] This achievement altered the nanoscience landscape and paved the way for a slew of new potential applications, including biomedical diagnostics, revolutionary photovoltaic cells, and LED materials.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Given that a nanocrystal is virtually all surface and no interior, its properties can vary considerably as the crystal grows in size.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Prior to Alivisatos's research, all non-metal nanocrystals were dot-shaped, meaning they were essentially one-dimensional.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] No techniques had been reported for making two-dimensional or rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals that would also be of uniform size.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] However, in a landmark paper that appeared in the March 2, 2000, issue of the journal Nature, Alivisatos reported on techniques used to select the size but vary the shapes of the nanocrystals produced.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] This was hailed as a major breakthrough in nanocrystal fabrication because rod-shaped semiconductor nanocrystals can be stacked to create nano-sized electronic devices.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos went on to use his techniques to create an entirely new generation of hybrid solar cells that combined nanotechnology with plastic electronics.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding scientist of Quantum Dot Corporation, a company that makes crystalline nanoscale tags that are used in the study of cell behavior.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] (Quantum Dot is now part of Life Technologies.) He also founded the nanotechnology company Nanosys, and Solexant, a photovoltaic start-up that has since restarted as Siva Power.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is the founding editor of *Nano Letters*, a publication of the American Chemical Society.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He formerly served on the Senior Editorial Board of *Science*.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He has also served on the editorial advisory boards of*ACS Nano*, the *Journal of Physical Chemistry*, *Chemical Physics*, the *Journal of Chemical Physics*, and *Advanced Materials*.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] In addition to those listed above, Alivisatos has held fellowships with the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the American Physical Society (1996), and the American Chemical Society.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] He is a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:detlev-bronk/a-paul-alivisatos] Alivisatos is married to Nicole Alivisatos, a retired chemist, former editor of the journal Nano Letters, and daughter of the noted chemist, Gábor A.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Abel Wolman was born to Louis and Rose Wachsman Wolman on June 10, 1892 in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] He was the fourth eldest child of Polish-Jewish immigrants.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Wolman received his high school education from the Baltimore City College in 1909.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Following his high school education, Wolman received his Bachelor of Arts in 1913 as a pre-med major.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Although Wolman was interested in becoming a doctor, his mother's insistence on studying engineering led him to pursue a degree in engineering.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] He then went on to complete a Bachelor of Science in Engineering at the Johns Hopkins University, graduating in 1915 as the fourth person to receive a degree at the newly-established Whiting School of Engineering.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Although Wolman did not complete a doctorate degree, his work in the field of sanitary engineering led to him being awarded an honorary Doctor of Engineering in 1937.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Wolman was also awarded a Doctor of Humane Letters from the Maryland Institute College of Arts and a Doctor of Law by the Johns Hopkins University in 1969.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Wolman served an extensive career in sanitary engineering, working in both environmental and public health services as well as in academics.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1914, he started his long career in public health as an assistant engineer working for the United States Public Health Service.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1922, Wolman became the Chief Engineer of the Maryland State Department of Health, where he served for 18 years until 1939.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] While working in the public health sector, Wolman conducted research related to sanitation and public health.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] He is best known for his 1919 contribution, with chemist Linn Enslow, in the standardization of chlorinating Baltimore's drinking-water supply.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] His efforts there helped develop the plan for Baltimore's water supply so thoroughly and effectively that it remains well-provided for growth through the 21st century.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] His work also benefited water systems in New York, Detroit and Columbus, Ohio.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] At that same time, he served as the Department of Sanitary Engineering's chairman until his official retirement in 1962.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] During his time as a sanitary engineering lecturer, he was asked to lecture at many prestigious universities, including Harvard University, Princeton University, University of Southern California, and University of Chicago.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] He was appointed Professor Emeritus in 1962, but had no desire to retire from professional life, so he continued his teaching and research in addition to serving as a consultant to the many governments and municipalities that requested his advice and assistance.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Supplementing his professional life, Wolman also held many important positions in the committees of professional societies and journal publications.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1916, he joined the American Public Health Association as an associate editor of the organization's monthly publication, *American Journal of Public Health,* where he eventually became the editor in 1955 until 1957.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Within the American Public Health Association, Wolman served as Chairman of the Public Health Engineering Section and Chairman of the Committee on Research and Standards.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Through their marriage, Wolman had one son, named Markley (M.) Gordon Wolman.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Maintaining a lively and witty personality, Wolman was favorable amongst many of the students he interacted with as a professor.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] From colleagues and family members that knew Wolman well, he has been described as being very well-organized and always perceptive towards his problems and analyses related to work.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Wolman died at his home in Baltimore, Maryland on February 22, 1989, aged 96 years old.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In collaboration with Linn Enslow, Wolman wanted to standardize a chlorination method to purify municipal water supplies.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] At the time, the purification of water with chlorine was known and employed in cities, but the problem that Wolman and Enslow highlighted in this publication was that the dosage of chlorine used by cities were unreliable and unscientific.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] As a result, municipal water supplies were often incorrectly purified, leading to failures in performance marked by diseases.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Wolman and Enslow began their experiment by describing their observations on the rate of chlorine absorption in different water samples that varied in bacteria, color, turbidity, oxidizable compounds, and other purity factors.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In "The Metabolism of Cities", Wolman highlighted three major "metabolic" problems that plagued major cities in the United States and offered his insight on the reality of those problems and possible solutions.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] He defined the metabolic requirements of a city as all materials and commodities needed to sustain its population, including all processes related to the proper removal and disposal of waste products produced in daily life.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] However, he pointed out that many major US cities share three metabolic problems: (1) lack of an adequate water supply, (2) ineffective disposal of sewage, and (3) poor control of air pollution.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Throughout most of the paper, Wolman provided relevant statistics and figures to underscore the proposed metabolic problems and analyzed historical municipal proposals designed to alleviate those metabolic problems.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] He concluded the article on a somewhat optimistic note, mentioning that the future of water sanitation, sewage disposal, and eliminating air pollutants is hopeful.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] However, in order to reach that future, Wolman called for immediate action and planning of policies and programs needed to combat the three metabolic problems.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Since the publication of this paper, there have been many studies performed to develop viable solutions to tackle the water shortages, waste disposal, and air pollution issues proposed by Wolman.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] For example, in 1999, civil and environmental engineers at the University of California, Berkeley published a research paper that confirmed the presence of water shortages in the United States and advocated for cities to take water recycling and reuse measures.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] For his efforts in public health practices and engineering skills on a local and global level, Wolman was granted multiple awards.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1948, Wolman was awarded the Sedgwick Memorial Medal by the American Public Health Association for his contributions in the field of public health.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1960, he was awarded the Albert Lasker Special Award in Public Health, which is an award "for outstanding contributions in research related to diseases which are the main causes of death and disability and for distinguished service in the field of public health administration.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1967, Wolman was awarded the William Procter Prize for Scientific Achievement for his contributions in the field of science.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1968, Wolman was awarded the first Lewis L.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1973, Wolman was awarded the Milton Stover Eisenhower Medal.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1974, Wolman was awarded the National Medal of Science.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1976, Wolman was awarded the Tyler Prize for Environmental Achievement and the Ben Gurion Award.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Both in 1973 and 1977, Wolman was awarded the American Water Works Association Award.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1986, Wolman was awarded the Robert E.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Horton Medal and the John Wesley Powell Award.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Finally, in 1999, The Baltimore Sun named Wolman "Marylander of the Century".
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] Following the death of Wolman, multiple tributes were created in his honor.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] For individuals that work in the water industry, the American Water Works Association annually presents the Abel Wolman Award of Excellence since 1985.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In May 1966, the Johns Hopkins University named a newly acquired dormitory Wolman Hall, which continues to house first year students.
[src:detlev-bronk/abel-wolman] In 1986, the City of Baltimore renamed its public works building to the Abel Wolman Municipal Building, honoring his years of service to the city.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:detlev-bronk/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] A 2002 survey ranked Bandura as the fourth most frequently cited psychologist of all time, behind B.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Skinner, Sigmund Freud, and Jean Piaget.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In April 2025, Bandura became the first psychologist with more than a million Google Scholar citations.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] During his lifetime, Bandura was widely described as the greatest living psychologist, and as one of the most influential psychologists of all time.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura was born in Mundare, Alberta, an open town of roughly 400 inhabitants, as the youngest of six children.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The limitations of education in his remote town caused Bandura to become independent and self-motivated in terms of learning, and the primarily-developed traits proved helpful later in his career.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura was of Polish and Ukrainian descent; his father was from Kraków, Poland, while his mother was from Ukraine.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura's parents were a key influence in encouraging him to seek ventures out of the small hamlet they resided in.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The summer after finishing high school, Bandura worked in the Yukon to protect the Alaska Highway against sinking.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura later credited his work in the northern tundra as the origin of his interest in human psychopathology.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] His experience in the Yukon, where he was exposed to a subculture of drinking and gambling, helped broaden his perspective and scope of views on life.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura arrived in the United States in 1949 and was naturalized in 1956.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] He married Virginia Varns (1921–2011) in 1952, and they raised two daughters, Carol and Mary.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura took psychology courses in college and became passionate about the subject.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] He graduated after three years in 1949 with a B.A. from the University of British Columbia, winning the Bolocan Award in psychology, and then moved to the then-epicenter of psychology, the University of Iowa, from where he obtained his M.A. in 1951 and Ph.D. in clinical psychology in 1952.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Arthur Benton was his academic adviser at Iowa, giving Bandura a direct academic descent from William James, while Clark Hull and Kenneth Spence were influential collaborators.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] During his Iowa years, Bandura came to support a style of psychology that sought to investigate psychological phenomena through repeatable, experimental testing.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] His inclusion of such mental phenomena as imagery and representation, and his concept of reciprocal determinism, which postulated a relationship of mutual influence between an agent and its environment, marked a radical departure from the dominant behaviorism of the time.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Upon graduation, he completed his postdoctoral internship at the Wichita Guidance Center.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The following year, 1953, he accepted a teaching position at Stanford University, which he held until he became professor emeritus in 2010.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 1974, he was elected president of the American Psychological Association (APA), the world's largest association of psychologists.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura would later state the only reason he agreed to be in the running for the APA election was because he wanted his 15 minutes of fame without any intentions of being elected.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura was initially influenced by Robert Sears' work on familial antecedents of social behavior and identificatory learning and gave up his research of the psychoanalytic theory.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] He directed his initial research to the role of social modeling in human motivation, thought, and action.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In collaboration with Richard Walters, his first doctoral student, he engaged in studies of social learning and aggression.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Their joint efforts illustrated the critical role of modeling in human behavior and led to a program of research into the determinants and mechanisms of observational learning.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The initial phase of Bandura's research analyzed the foundations of human learning and the willingness of children and adults to imitate behavior that they observed in other people, particularly the emotion of aggression.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The research indicated models as an important means for learning new behaviors and for achieving behavioral change in an institutional setting.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Social learning theory posits three regulatory systems that control human behavior.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Response and feedback influences have an important function.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Following a response to a stimulus, the reinforcements, either by experience or by observation, will determine future occurrences of the behavior.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Cognitive functions are important in social learning.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] For example, for aggressive behavior to occur, some people are readily angered by the sight or the thought of persons with whom they had hostile encounters, and that aggression-inducing memory is learned.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Social learning theory became one of the theoretical frameworks for Entertainment-Education, a method of creating socially beneficial entertainment pioneered by Miguel Sabido.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura and Sabido went on to forge a close relationship and further refine the theory and practice.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] His research with Walters led to his first book, *Adolescent Aggression* (1959), followed by *Social Learning and Personality Development* (1963), and *Aggression: A Social Learning Analysis* (1973).
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] During a period dominated by behaviorism in the mold of B.F.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Skinner, Bandura believed the sole behavioral modifiers of reward and punishment in classical and operant conditioning were inadequate as a framework, and that many human behaviors were learned from other humans.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura began to analyze the means of treating unduly aggressive children by identifying sources of violence in their lives.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Initial research in the area had begun in the 1940s under Neal Miller and John Dollard; his continued work in this line eventually culminated in the Bobo doll experiment, which led to his 1977 treatise, *Social Learning Theory*.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Many of his innovations came from his focus on empirical investigation and reproducible investigation, contrary to Sigmund Freud's popular theories of psychoanalysis.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 1974, Stanford University awarded him an endowed chair and he became David Starr Jordan Professor of Social Science in Psychology.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 1961, Bandura conducted a controversial experiment known as the Bobo doll experiment, which was designed to show that similar behaviors were learned by individuals shaping their own behavior after the actions of models.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The experiment emphasized how young individuals are influenced by the acts of adults.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] When the adults were praised for their aggressive behavior, the children were more likely to keep on hitting the doll.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] However, when the adults were punished, they consequently stopped hitting the doll as well.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura's results from the experiment were widely credited with helping shift the focus in academic psychology from pure behaviorism to cognitive psychology.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] By the mid-1980s, Bandura's research had taken a more holistic bent, and his analysis tended toward giving a more comprehensive overview of human cognition in the context of social learning.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The theory he expanded from social learning theory soon became known as social cognitive theory.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The foundation of Bandura's social learning theory is the idea that people may learn by seeing and copying the observable behaviors of others.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] As an alternative to the earlier work of colleague psychologist B.F.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Skinner, who was well known for advocating the behaviorist theory, psychologists Bandura and Sears presented the social learning hypothesis.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 1986, Bandura published *Social Foundations of Thought and Action: A Social Cognitive Theory*, in which he re-conceptualized individuals as self-organizing, proactive, self-reflecting, and self-regulating, in opposition to the orthodox conception of humans as governed by external forces.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] He advanced concepts of triadic reciprocal causation, which determined the connections between human behavior, environmental factors, and personal factors such as cognitive, affective, and biological events, and of reciprocal determinism, governing the causal relations between such factors.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura's emphasis on the capacity of agents to self-organize and self-regulate would eventually give rise to his later work on self-efficacy.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] While investigating the processes by which modeling alleviates phobic disorders in snake-phobics, he found that self-efficacy beliefs (which the phobic individuals had in their own capabilities to alleviate their phobia) mediated changes in behavior and in fear-arousal.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] He launched a major program of research examining the influential role of self-referent thought in psychological functioning.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Although he continued to explore and write on theoretical problems relating to myriad topics, from the late 1970s, he devoted much attention to exploring the role of self-efficacy beliefs in human functioning.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 1986, he published *Social Foundations of Thought and Action: A Social Cognitive Theory*, a book in which he offered a social cognitive theory of human functioning that accords a central role to cognitive, vicarious, self-regulatory, and self-reflective processes in human adaptation and change.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] This theory has roots in an agentic perspective that views people as self-organizing, proactive, self-reflecting, and self-regulating, not just as reactive organisms shaped by environmental forces or driven by inner impulses.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] His book, *Self-Efficacy: The Exercise of Control* was published in 1997.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] The application of Bandura's self-efficacy research did not end with phobia-mediation, however, but extended into healthcare, particularly in the management of addictive behaviors such as smoking and smoking cessation.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In these interventions, an individual's confidence in their ability to resist cravings and high-risk triggers was found to be a strong predictor of relapse.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Successful, long-term maintenance of cessation and positive alterations in usage were consistently associated with higher self-efficacy, suggesting that emphasizing and enhancing one's confidence could reduce rates of relapse.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] These findings validate Bandura's theory and demonstrate ways in which targeting self-efficacy has predicted treatment outcomes in addictive behaviors.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura's social cognitive theories have been applied to education as well, mainly focusing on self-efficacy, self-regulation, observational learning, and reciprocal determinism.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura's research showed that high perceived self-efficacy led teachers and students to set higher goals, and it increased the likelihood that they would dedicate themselves to those goals.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In an educational setting, self-efficacy refers to a student or teacher's confidence to participate in certain actions that will help them achieve distinct goals.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] Bandura died at his home in Stanford, on July 26, 2021, from congestive heart failure, at the age of 95.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] He was elected a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1980.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] He received the Award for Distinguished Scientific Contributions from the American Psychological Association (APA) in 1980 for pioneering the research in the field of self-regulated learning.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 1999, he received the Thorndike Award for Distinguished Contributions of Psychology to Education from the APA, and in 2001, he received the Lifetime Achievement Award from the Association for the Advancement of Behavior Therapy.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 2008, he received the University of Louisville Grawemeyer Award for contributions to psychology.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 2014, he was made an Officer of the Order of Canada "for his foundational contributions to social psychology, notably for uncovering the influence of observation on human learning and aggression".
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-bandura] In 2016, he was awarded the National Medal of Science by president Barack Obama.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:detlev-bronk/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] Bronk was a descendant of Pieter Bronck, an early settler to New Netherland for whose relative Jonas Bronck the New York City borough The Bronx is named.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] In 1920 Bronk graduated with a B.S. in electrical engineering from Swarthmore College, where he was a member of Phi Kappa Psi fraternity.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] In September 1921 Bronk married Helen Alexander Ramsey, who had been a fellow student at Swarthmore.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] Turning to physics, he received an M.S. in 1922 from the University of Michigan.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] By 1924 he was intent on applying physics and mathematics to physiology, receiving a Ph.D. in 1926 from the University of Michigan.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] Benjy Bronk, a frequent contributor to the Howard Stern show, is his Great Nephew.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] When Bronk was offered the presidency of Johns Hopkins University in 1948, he accepted the position on the condition that Hopkins strengthen its program in biophysics.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] Hopkins did just that, building Jenkins Hall in 1950 specifically to house Biophysics and adding faculty and research facilities.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] Bronk believed the nation's universities had a responsibility to prepare students to improve the world, regardless of their academic curriculum.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] He also recognized that, during World War II, the Hopkins faculty had spent most of their time performing defense-related research, and now it was time to rejuvenate the idea of research for the sake of learning and discovery.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] In addition to guiding Hopkins through its post-war "demobilization," Bronk believed strongly in maintaining his own presence in the scientific community.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] He presided over the National Academy of Sciences and served on boards for the American Association for the Advancement of Science, the Science Advisory Committee of the Office of Defense Mobilization, and the National Advisory Committee for Aeronautics (predecessor to NASA).
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] Bronk was also instrumental in reviving a plan to abolish undergraduate education at Johns Hopkins and turn Hopkins into a graduate-only institution.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] In 1952, as in 1925, the "New Plan" or "Bronk Plan" would have phased out the freshman and sophomore years and Hopkins would only admit students transferring from other institutions as juniors or above.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] These students would bypass the traditional undergraduate degree and begin work immediately toward a doctorate.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] As in 1925, the plan attracted little support from the intended student body and it was quietly dropped by the mid-1950s after Prof.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] Bronk was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1934 and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1949.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] From 1953 to 1968 Bronk was president of The Rockefeller University.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] (The Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research was renamed The Rockefeller University in 1965).
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] He firmly espoused academic freedom and resisted attempts by Wisconsin Senator Joseph McCarthy to have Johns Hopkins University dismiss Professor Owen Lattimore.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] The same year he was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] He was credited with formulating the modern theory of the science of biophysics.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] He served on the board of trustees for Science Service, now known as Society for Science & the Public, from 1965 to 1967.
[src:detlev-bronk/detlev-bronk] Bronk crater on the Moon was named after him in 1979.
